1.1 Question 1

Plot the Exports series for selected country and discuss the main features of the data.

## [1] 1
## # A tibble: 58 × 2
##    Country Exports
##    <fct>     <dbl>
##  1 Italy      12.5
##  2 Italy      12.8
##  3 Italy      12.7
##  4 Italy      12.2
##  5 Italy      12.8
##  6 Italy      14.3
##  7 Italy      14.7
##  8 Italy      14.5
##  9 Italy      15.2
## 10 Italy      15.8
## # ℹ 48 more rows

The Italian exports data is interesting from a historical context. Overall, there is an increasing trend over a 58 year time span starting in 1960. About two decades later, there was an economic recession that severely impacted this specific industry. This decline occurred for about 10 years until the early 1990s. Then, the devaluation of the lira sparked an increase in moving goods because it made Italian exports more competitive in foreign markets. Although there does not seem to be seasonality, the increasing trend repetitively falls and rises for several years until the recession in 2008. This caused trouble in the Italian exports because the demand for certain products that they were leading manufacturers in significantly decreased. After this period of turmoil, they managed to get their export trend moving in a positive direction.

If seasonality were present, there would be larger seasonal lags at specific frequencies appearing multiple times. Unfortunately, these types of patterns do not appear. As stated earlier, an overall positive trend for the Italian exports is seen, and the correlogram shows what will happen x lags after the nearest observation in time. The smaller lags are quite larger as the lags continue in time. This means that ‘the ACF trended time series tend to have positive values that slowly decrease as the lags increase.’ Additionally, when one or more spikes are outside of the dashed lines, it means that the series is most likely not white noise.

As the lags increase, the relationship between annual Italian exports become weaker. This is seen as the data points are not aligning with the dotted line because the data continues to disperse.

1.2 Question 2

Use one of the viewed methods (simple exponential smoothing, Holt, Holt-Winter) which is appropriated to your series. Justify your choice. Comment on your model’s parameter(s). How well does your model fit the data?

1.2.1 SES (naïve)

Method: No trend, no seasonality

##                      ACF1
## Training set -0.007011304

The best \(\alpha\) is 0.91 because the RMSE is the lowest at 1.35. The SES method forecasts that all points within the time series are equally weighted to the last observed value. Since this is not optimal, typically one would seek to put larger weights on most recent observations and less to those father away. As the \(\alpha\) value increases, the model will put more weight to the most recent observations.

  • Forecast equation: \(\hat{y}_{t+h|t} = l_t\)
  • Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}{y_t} + (1 - \alpha)l_{t-1}\)

Method: Trend, no seasonality

## ETS(A,Ad,N)

## 
## Training set error measures:

## Training set 0.0743749 1.304402 0.9661937 0.06856984 4.637248 0.9475726
##                      ACF1
## Training set -0.001637108

In Holt’s model, this allows the SES to be extended to include the trend within the forecast data. In practice, this means that the forecast function is not considered flat but is trending. According to the book, ’the h-step-ahead forecast is equal to the last estimated level plus h times the last estimated trend value. Hence the forecasts are a linear function of h. In addition to the SES equations, Holt’s linear method introduces \(\beta\), the slope.

  • Forecast equation: \(\hat{y}_{t+h|t} = l_t\)
  • Level equation: \(l_t = {\alpha}{y_t} + (1 - \alpha)l_{t-1}\)
  • Trend equation: \(b_t = {\beta}*({l_t} - l_{t-1})\)

Additionally, the damped trend method was used in Holt’s model. Realistically, a constant positive or negative trend continuing indefinitely into the future is most likely not going to occur. Therefore, damping a trend means that it is flatten into the years to come.

1.2.5 Holt-Winter Method

Method: Trend, Seasonality
Since there have been multiple models showing that seasonality within the trended data does not exist, this method will not be ran in R since it uses an additional smoothing equation to account for frequency of that constant variation in seasons.

Overall, the Holt Undamped model seems to be the most appropriate. The SES would not be considered as the method does not take into account a trend. Therefore, the graph shows a constant flat line for the for the next four observations which is not realistic when discussing Italian exports. The optimal RMSE was 1.34 with a smoothing parameter (\(\alpha\)) at 0.9999. The Hot-Winter model is immediately ruled out since the correlogram shows no pattern of seasonality. The best method is Holt’s due to the nature of the trending data. The next question to raise though is if the model should be dampened. According to the RMSEs (best fit) of the two models, the undamped methods seems to be slightly better with a RMSE of 1.295 compared to 1.304. But, as the book mentioned, the damped methods have been proven to be exceedingly successful. This decision is a toss up due to the closeness of the RMSEs and the measure of dampness. Therefore, the recommended model would be Holt Undamped. To ensure that this is the right model though, discussing with an expert is crucial. For this method, there are three parameters to take into consideration.

  1. \(\hat{\alpha}\): The estimated smoothing coefficient is 0.9999. As the value is extremely close to 1, this means that the ‘level changes rapidly in order to capture the highly trended series.’
  2. \(\hat{\beta}\): The estimated smoothing coefficient for the slope is .00001. This means that the slope does not change often even if there are slight changes.
  3. \(\phi\): \(\phi\) represents the dampened effect. The value is 0.9796, which suggests that the damped model is not able to be distinguished from a non-damped model. Since the effect is very close to 1, it is not likely that this model would be used. To verify though, a subject matter expert should be involved.

Since China is the largest exporter in the world, it made sense to look at their data to see if it differed from how Italy exports. The country’s export trend is relatively positive, and there appears to be no sign of seasonality according to the ACF chart. From the early 2000s, there was a steep incline of exports and this was due to factors such as China joining the World Trade Organization, expansion of manufacturing sector, and trade surplus among a few. Just as exports fell in Italy in around 2008, the same thing happened to China. Unfortunately, they did not recover as quickly since their trend seems to be declining now which could be due to other economic factors. Since a trend is present, Holt’s model would be the best. The difference for China though is that the better model is one with the damped effect of 80% as the RMSE is 1.85 compared to 1.91 with undamped.
